<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Unit launch. One question runs through the whole unit: <em>who owns the water?</em></p>
  <p>That question only makes sense once you understand what water <em>is</em> — physically. The water cycle isn't trivia; it's the structure of the political problem. Today builds the cycle in detail: <strong>reservoirs</strong> (where water sits — atmosphere, soil moisture, rivers, lakes, groundwater, ocean, ice sheets) and <strong>residence times</strong> (how long water stays in each — atmosphere ~10 days, soil ~weeks-to-months, rivers ~weeks, lakes ~years, groundwater ~decades-to-millennia, ocean ~millennia, ice sheets ~tens of thousands of years).</p>
  <p>Why residence time matters: it's why some water disputes are negotiable and others aren't. River allocations can be renegotiated — water cycles through fast. A depleted aquifer can't be renegotiated on human timescales — the water is gone for centuries. The <strong>Cauvery dispute</strong> (Tamil Nadu vs. Karnataka, the unit's anchor case) is fundamentally a fast-reservoir conflict (river allocation) layered on top of a slow-reservoir crisis (groundwater depletion across both states). Today opens that tension.</p>
</section>

