<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — choose one path</h2>
  <p class="sub">All four paths end with a labeled water-cycle diagram + an exit ticket connecting one reservoir to one Cauvery-dispute stakeholder. The path you pick is about how you build the diagram.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I can describe the Cauvery dispute in 3 sentences, name at least 3 stakeholders affected by it, and pose 2 questions about water rights that the dispute raises.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">A</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Standard paired water-cycle diagram (default)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Pair work. Draw a labeled water-cycle diagram showing reservoirs, fluxes, and residence times. Use the vocabulary from the Read handout. Submit one diagram per pair.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Default</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">B</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Cauvery-specific diagram (stretch)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Same as Path A, but add the Cauvery basin's specific reservoirs — Krishna Raja Sagar (Karnataka), Mettur (Tamil Nadu), the groundwater aquifers beneath both states, the river itself, the delta wetlands. Arrows show inter-state flow. This is the diagram you'll reference in Block 4 and beyond.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Stretch</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">C</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Hydrologist consultation (choice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Open the <a href="/ai-partners/the-hydrologist/">Hydrologist</a>. Ask one specific question about a reservoir or residence time you're unsure about. Document the exchange — this is your first AI Doc entry for Unit 5.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Solo · Choice</span>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">D</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Peer-help — residence time vs. flow rate (practice)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Often confused. Residence time is "how long water stays"; flow rate is "how fast water moves through." If the distinction is fuzzy, come to the peer-help table. Pair with a student who's solid. Mr. Ignash floats.</div>
      <span class="udl-tag">Pairs · Practice</span>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="block-section show">
  <span class="section-tag">Show</span>
  <h2>What you're submitting today</h2>
  <p class="sub">One reservoir + one residence time + one stakeholder connection. Specificity is the bar.</p>
  <div class="submission-callout">
    <div class="label">Exit ticket — reservoir + residence time + stakeholder claim</div>
    <p>Three things: (1) name a water reservoir in the Cauvery basin · (2) state its approximate residence time · (3) identify one Cauvery-dispute stakeholder whose claim depends on that reservoir, and why. Generic ("groundwater" / "long" / "farmers") doesn't clear the bar. Specific is the move — e.g., "The shallow aquifer beneath the Cauvery delta has a residence time of decades. Tamil Nadu delta rice farmers depend on it for dry-season irrigation; depletion is irreversible on the timescale of their livelihoods."</p>
    <a href="#" class="rubric-link">Submit via Google Classroom →</a>
  </div>
  <p class="rubric-meta">
    <strong>Rubric link:</strong> Specific reservoir + residence-time + stakeholder linkage is K/U bedrock for the <a href="/units/unit-5/assessment-water-stakeholders/">Water Stakeholders Map + Position Paper</a>. The K/U 7-8 band requires "specific stakeholders" — that practice starts today. See the <a href="/foundations/the-rubric/">rubric</a>.
  </p>
</section>

